<ReportItem port="445" svc_name="cifs" protocol="tcp" severity="0" pluginID="96982" pluginName="Server Message Block (SMB) Protocol Version 1 Enabled (uncredentialed check)" pluginFamily="Misc.">
<description>The remote host (Windows and/or Samba server) supports Server Message Block Protocol version 1 (SMBv1). Microsoft recommends that users discontinue the use of SMBv1 due to the lack of security features that were included in later SMB versions. Additionally, most security and compliance agencies recommend that users disable SMBv1 per SMB best practices.</description>
<fname>smb_v1_enabled_remote.nasl</fname>
<iavt>0001-T-0710</iavt>
<in_the_news>true</in_the_news>
<plugin_modification_date>2025/08/13</plugin_modification_date>
<plugin_name>Server Message Block (SMB) Protocol Version 1 Enabled (uncredentialed check)</plugin_name>
<plugin_publication_date>2017/02/03</plugin_publication_date>
<plugin_type>remote</plugin_type>
<risk_factor>None</risk_factor>
<script_version>1.8</script_version>
<see_also>http://www.nessus.org/u?59bfc3ef
http://www.nessus.org/u?b9d9ebf9
http://www.nessus.org/u?8dcab5e4
http://www.nessus.org/u?234f8ef8
http://www.nessus.org/u?4c7e0cf3</see_also>
<solution>Disable SMBv1 according to the vendor instructions in Microsoft KB2696547. Additionally, block SMB directly by blocking TCP port 445 on all network boundary devices. For SMB over the NetBIOS API, block TCP ports 137 / 139 and UDP ports 137 / 138 on all network boundary devices.</solution>
<synopsis>The remote host supports the SMBv1 protocol.</synopsis>
<xref>IAVT:0001-T-0710</xref>
<plugin_output>
The remote host supports SMBv1.
</plugin_output>
</ReportItem>
